[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Reference implementations:** The following AWS sample resources demonstrate the patterns used in this recipe:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m >
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > - [Amazon HealthLake Documentation](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/healthlake/latest/devguide/what-is-amazon-health-lake.html): The FHIR datastore that backs the longitudinal patient timeline used here for current-state and training data
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > - [`amazon-sagemaker-examples`](https://github.com/aws/amazon-sagemaker-examples): Official SageMaker examples including custom-container patterns for survival models and time-series forecasting
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > - [AWS Step Functions Workflow Studio](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/step-functions/latest/dg/workflow-studio.html): For visually composing the inference and retraining pipelines
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): N2. Verify all reference implementation links are still live during the pre-publication audit. -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 1: Snapshot the current hospital state.** Every forecast cycle starts by capturing the current state of every occupied bed: which patient, on which unit, admitted at what time, with what working DRG, with what discharge order status. The snapshot is the anchor for the rest of the forecast; getting it wrong means every subsequent step is calibrated to a fiction.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION snapshot_current_state(snapshot_ts):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Pull current state from the FHIR datastore. We want every Encounter
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // that is currently in-progress (Encounter.status = "in-progress").
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     active_encounters = healthlake_search_encounters(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         status     = "in-progress",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         as_of_ts   = snapshot_ts
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state_records = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each encounter in active_encounters:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Pull the per-patient features needed by the survival model.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // These come from a mix of FHIR resources: the Encounter itself
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // (admission ts, current location, service type), Condition
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // resources (diagnoses), MedicationRequest resources (active meds),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // ServiceRequest resources (pending consults, pending procedures),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // and ClinicalImpression resources (discharge planning notes).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient_features = build_patient_features(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             encounter            = encounter,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient_id           = encounter.subject_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             as_of_ts             = snapshot_ts
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // The single most important feature: has a discharge order
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // been entered? "Discharge order entered" is a strong predictor
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // of discharge in the next 6 hours. Other status hints (planned
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // disposition, anticipated discharge date documented in care plan)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // also matter, but the discharge order is the discrete signal.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient_features.discharge_order_entered = check_discharge_order(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             encounter_id  = encounter.id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             as_of_ts      = snapshot_ts
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // LOS so far (in hours, not days). The survival model uses
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // this as a feature; downstream operational displays show it
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // in days.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient_features.los_hours_so_far = (snapshot_ts - encounter.admit_ts).hours
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         record = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             encounter_id:       encounter.id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient_id:         encounter.subject_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             current_unit:       encounter.location.unit_code,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             admit_ts:           encounter.admit_ts,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             service_line:       encounter.service_type,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             attending_id:       encounter.participant.attending,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             features:           patient_features,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             snapshot_ts:        snapshot_ts
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         state_records.append(record)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     write state_records to S3 inference-features/snapshots/ partitioned by snapshot_ts
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN state_records
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 2: Forecast inflows by source, service, and unit.** Run the inflow models for the forecast horizon. Different sources use different methods. The output is, for each forecast hour and each candidate admit unit, an expected admission count plus a sample distribution suitable for Monte Carlo composition.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION forecast_inflows(snapshot_ts, horizon_hours, n_samples = 1000):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     inflow_samples = []  // shape: [n_samples, horizon_hours, n_units]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // ED-driven admissions: Poisson regression on calendar + weather +
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // current-ED-state features. The current ED census and current ED
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // hold count are strong short-horizon features (an ED with 9 holds
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // right now will produce admissions within the next 4 hours with
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // high probability).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ed_admit_features = build_ed_admit_features(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         snapshot_ts   = snapshot_ts,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         horizon_hours = horizon_hours
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ed_admit_samples = sagemaker_invoke(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         endpoint = "ed-admit-poisson-endpoint",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         payload  = {features: ed_admit_features, n_samples: n_samples}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // ed_admit_samples shape: [n_samples, horizon_hours]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // (this is the count; unit assignment is a separate step)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // OR schedule: deterministic. Read the schedule for the next
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // horizon, multiply each scheduled case by historical show-rate
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // and case-completion rate. The case end-time plus historical
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // PACU-to-floor delay gives the expected admit timestamp.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     or_schedule       = read_or_schedule(snapshot_ts, horizon_hours)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     surgical_admits   = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each case in or_schedule:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         show_probability = lookup_show_rate(case.service_line, case.day_of_week)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         post_op_delay_hours = lookup_pacu_delay(case.service_line)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         expected_admit_ts = case.scheduled_end_ts + post_op_delay_hours
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         post_op_unit      = lookup_post_op_unit(case.surgery_type)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF expected_admit_ts < snapshot_ts + horizon_hours:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             surgical_admits.append({
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 expected_admit_ts: expected_admit_ts,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 probability:       show_probability,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 target_unit:       post_op_unit
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             })
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Direct admits: simple Poisson with day-of-week features.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     direct_admit_samples = sagemaker_invoke(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         endpoint = "direct-admit-poisson-endpoint",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         payload  = {features: build_direct_admit_features(snapshot_ts), n_samples: n_samples}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Transfers in: read the transfer center queue for known near-term
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // transfers, plus a Poisson model for unknown transfers beyond the
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // queue's lead time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     queued_transfers = read_transfer_center_queue(snapshot_ts)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     transfer_in_samples = sagemaker_invoke(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         endpoint = "transfer-in-poisson-endpoint",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         payload  = {features: build_transfer_features(snapshot_ts), n_samples: n_samples}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Unit assignment: for each ED-driven and direct admit count, sample
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // the unit assignment from the multinomial classifier. The classifier
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // takes the admission's features (chief complaint or diagnosis,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // service line, age) and returns a probability distribution over
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // candidate units.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     inflow_samples = compose_inflow_samples(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ed_admit_samples       = ed_admit_samples,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         surgical_admits        = surgical_admits,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         direct_admit_samples   = direct_admit_samples,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         transfer_in_samples    = transfer_in_samples,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         queued_transfers       = queued_transfers,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         unit_assignment_endpoint = "unit-assignment-classifier-endpoint",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         n_samples              = n_samples
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     write inflow_samples to S3 forecast-samples/inflows/ partitioned by snapshot_ts
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN inflow_samples
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: Predict per-patient discharge probabilities over the horizon.** For every currently-admitted patient, predict the probability they discharge in each hour of the forecast horizon. The survival model takes the per-patient features from Step 1 plus the hour-of-day pattern of discharges and produces a discharge-time distribution. Sample from these distributions to produce per-unit discharge counts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION forecast_outflows(state_records, horizon_hours, n_samples = 1000):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // For each currently-admitted patient, get a discharge-time
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // distribution over the next horizon_hours.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     discharge_distributions = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each record in state_records:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Survival model returns a hazard function over the horizon:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // for each hour h in [0, horizon_hours], P(discharge in [h, h+1) | survived to h).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         hazard_function = sagemaker_invoke(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             endpoint = "discharge-survival-endpoint",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             payload  = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 features:       record.features,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 horizon_hours:  horizon_hours
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Convert hazard to cumulative discharge probability.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         cumulative_discharge_p = cumulative_from_hazard(hazard_function)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         discharge_distributions.append({
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             encounter_id:           record.encounter_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             current_unit:           record.current_unit,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             cumulative_discharge_p: cumulative_discharge_p
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         })
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Sample N times: for each patient, draw a discharge time from
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // their distribution (or "no discharge in horizon"). Aggregate
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // by (sample, hour, unit) into discharge counts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     outflow_samples = []  // shape: [n_samples, horizon_hours, n_units]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR sample_id in 1..n_samples:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         sample_grid = zero_grid(horizon_hours, n_units)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each dd in discharge_distributions:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             discharge_hour = sample_discharge_hour(dd.cumulative_discharge_p, horizon_hours)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             IF discharge_hour is not null:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 sample_grid[discharge_hour][dd.current_unit] += 1
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         outflow_samples[sample_id] = sample_grid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     write outflow_samples to S3 forecast-samples/outflows/ partitioned by snapshot_ts
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN outflow_samples
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 4: Compose census trajectories with Monte Carlo.** Take the current state, the inflow samples, and the outflow samples, and walk forward sample by sample to produce per-sample census trajectories. Aggregate across samples to get the expected occupancy and prediction intervals per (unit, hour). The composition step is also where bed-management overflow rules get applied: if a unit's projected occupancy exceeds capacity in a sample, the overflow logic redistributes admissions to designated overflow units.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION compose_census(state_records, inflow_samples, outflow_samples, horizon_hours, unit_capacities, overflow_rules):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     n_samples = inflow_samples.shape[0]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     n_units   = inflow_samples.shape[2]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    445[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    446[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Initial state: count current occupants per unit from state_records.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    447[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     initial_census = count_by_unit(state_records)  // shape: [n_units]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    448[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    449[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     census_trajectories = []  // shape: [n_samples, horizon_hours, n_units]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    450[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    451[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR sample_id in 1..n_samples:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    452[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         census = copy(initial_census)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    453[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         trajectory = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    454[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR hour in 0..horizon_hours-1:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    455[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Apply this sample's outflows for this hour.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    456[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             FOR unit in 0..n_units-1:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    457[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 census[unit] -= outflow_samples[sample_id][hour][unit]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    458[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 census[unit] = max(census[unit], 0)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    459[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    460[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Apply this sample's inflows for this hour, with overflow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    461[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             FOR unit in 0..n_units-1:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    462[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 proposed_admits = inflow_samples[sample_id][hour][unit]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    463[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 available_capacity = unit_capacities[unit] - census[unit]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    464[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    465[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 IF proposed_admits <= available_capacity:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    466[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     // Fits in target unit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    467[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     census[unit] += proposed_admits
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    468[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    469[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     // Overflow: place what fits, route the rest per the
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    470[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     // overflow rules.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    471[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     fits = max(available_capacity, 0)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    472[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     census[unit] += fits
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    473[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     overflow_count = proposed_admits - fits
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    474[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     overflow_targets = overflow_rules[unit]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    475[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     distribute_overflow(census, overflow_count, overflow_targets, unit_capacities)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    476[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    477[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             trajectory.append(copy(census))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    478[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         census_trajectories[sample_id] = trajectory
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    479[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    480[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Aggregate across samples per (hour, unit).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    481[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     forecast = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    482[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR hour in 0..horizon_hours-1:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    483[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR unit in 0..n_units-1:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    484[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             sample_values = [census_trajectories[s][hour][unit] FOR s in 1..n_samples]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    485[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             forecast.append({
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    486[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 unit_id:                   unit,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    487[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 forecast_for_ts:           snapshot_ts + hour hours,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    488[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 expected_occupancy:        mean(sample_values),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    489[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 p10_occupancy:             percentile(sample_values, 10),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    490[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 p50_occupancy:             percentile(sample_values, 50),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    491[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 p90_occupancy:             percentile(sample_values, 90),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    492[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 capacity:                  unit_capacities[unit],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    493[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 expected_utilization_pct:  mean(sample_values) / unit_capacities[unit],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    494[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 generated_at_ts:           snapshot_ts,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    495[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 model_version:             current_model_version_string
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    496[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             })
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    497[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    498[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     write forecast to S3 forecasts/ partitioned by snapshot_ts
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    499[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN forecast
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    500[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    501[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    502[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 5: Deliver forecasts to operational consumers.** The bed huddle dashboard, the transfer center, the OR scheduler, and the ED diversion tool all read from DynamoDB. Writing the forecast atomically per cycle (with a generated_at_ts attribute) lets consumers identify whether they're showing fresh or stale data and lets the dashboard render staleness explicitly when the pipeline misses a cycle.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    503[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    504[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    505[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION deliver_forecast(forecast, table_name):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    506[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Write forecasts to DynamoDB. Partition key is unit_id; sort key
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    507[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // is forecast_for_ts. This keeps all forecasts for a given unit
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    508[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // in one partition for efficient horizon queries.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    509[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     batches = chunk forecast into groups of 25
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    510[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each batch in batches:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    511[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         write batch to DynamoDB table_name with:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    512[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             partition_key = unit_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    513[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             sort_key      = forecast_for_ts
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    514[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             attributes    = full forecast object
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    515[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         retry unprocessed items with exponential backoff
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    516[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    517[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Emit CloudWatch metrics: forecast volume, generation time, count
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    518[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // of unit-hours where p90 exceeds capacity (the "predicted gridlock"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    519[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // metric the operations team most wants to track).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    520[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     gridlock_count = count(forecast where p90_occupancy > capacity)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    521[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     emit_cloudwatch_metric("forecast.unit_hours", forecast.length)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    522[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     emit_cloudwatch_metric("forecast.predicted_gridlock_unit_hours", gridlock_count)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    523[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     emit_cloudwatch_metric("forecast.generation_seconds", elapsed_seconds)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    524[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    525[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Optional: post a summary message to the bed huddle channel if
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    526[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // gridlock unit-hours exceed the alerting threshold.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    527[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF gridlock_count > alert_threshold:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    528[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         post_to_bed_huddle_channel(summary_for(forecast))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    529[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    530[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN { forecast_count: forecast.length, gridlock_count: gridlock_count }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    531[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    532[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    533[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, statsmodels for inflow forecasting, lifelines or PySurvival for the outflow model, and NumPy for the Monte Carlo composition, check out the [Python Example](chapter12.05-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    534[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    535[0m:[38;5;10m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): N3. The Python companion file (chapter12.05-python-example.md) is referenced here but does not yet exist in this branch. Confirm it has been drafted before publishing this recipe. -->
